# ======================================================================
# iv_surface_forecast_pipeline.py
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------
# Cross-sectional monthly stock-return forecasting from OptionMetrics
# implied-volatility (IV) SURFACES, treated as 10 x 18 "images".
#
# This adapts the univariate VIX time-series pipeline
# (vix_multimodel_forecast_pipeline.py) to the methodology of
#
#   Kelly, Kuznetsov, Malamud & Xu (2026),
#   "Deep Learning from Implied Volatility Surfaces", SSRN 4531181.
#
# Paper recap (what we replicate):
#   * Input  : OptionMetrics IvyDB IV surface on the last business day of
#              month t, reshaped to a 10 x 18 image
#              (delta in [-0.5,0.5], maturities ~20..730 days, ATM re-stacked).
#   * Target : next-month stock total/excess return R_{i,t+1}.
#   * Models : convolutional nets CNN1 / CNN4 / CNN5 (1/4/5 conv blocks,
#              3x3 conv -> 2x2 maxpool -> BatchNorm -> ReLU, filters
#              16/32/64/128, global-average-pool, single linear head).
#   * Ensemble: K random initialisations (K = 1..100), predictions averaged.
#   * Training: EXPANDING window. 7-year warm-up (1996-2002, 10 epochs),
#               then transfer-learning month-by-month (5 epochs/refit).
#               Adam, lr=1e-3, batch=512, Xavier init, MSE loss.
#   * Portfolio: each month sort stocks into deciles by predicted return,
#                equal-weight, long top decile / short bottom decile (H-L),
#                1-month holding. Report annualised Sharpe, ranked.
#                Size groups via NYSE breakpoints (mega/large/small/micro).
#
# Extensions in this file (the model "zoo" requested):
#   rf, deepmlp, cnn, cnn1, cnn4, cnn5, lstm, autoformer, esn,
#   cnn-lstm, cnn-autoformer, cnn-esn.
#   NOTE: the deep MLP keeps the name "deepmlp" everywhere (never "dp").
#
# YOUR DATA (auto-detected by the data-check stage):
#   per-stock pickle files such as  <something>_all_Count_w_fReturns.pickle
#   with id columns        : perm_id / perm_ID , date , trade_id
#   with target columns    : TRET_F50, TRET_F20D,
#                            TRET_SP500_EX_F50, TRET_SP500_EX_F20D, ...
#   with 180 surface cells : reshaped to (10, 18).
#   Primary target         : TRET_SP500_EX_F20D (next ~month excess return).
#
# NO LOOK-AHEAD (strictly enforced):
#   * features = month-end IV surface at t; target = forward return realised
#     at t+h.  Train/test are split BY THE REALISED TARGET DATE.
#   * a purge/embargo of `horizon` months is applied around the test start so
#     that no training target's holding window overlaps the test features.
#   * per-pixel feature scalers and the target scaler are fit on TRAIN ONLY
#     and merely applied to validation/test.
#   * the validation tail for early stopping is the chronological end of the
#     current training window (never future data).
#
# DELL / WINDOWS / 8GB-GPU FRIENDLY:
#   * CONFIG["use_cuda"] = False (or --no-cuda) -> pure CPU.
#   * GPU (neural) models run sequentially with small batches + AMP so they
#     fit in 8 GB of VRAM; CPU models (rf) fan out over a process pool
#     across the 20 cores (CONFIG["n_workers"]).
#   * spawn context, __main__ guard, torch lazily imported.
#
# EFFICIENCY:
#   * surfaces are reshaped/standardised with fully-vectorised numpy;
#   * the (target x model) grid runs in parallel where memory-safe;
#   * everything is cached to parquet/pickle between stages.
# ======================================================================
